Certainly! Below is an example of a simple web app that displays a big local time clock and a sidebar showing clocks from different cities around the world. It allows you to add new cities and stores them in local storage. 

You can copy the entire code block below and save it as an `.html` file. When you open it in your web browser, you'll be able to see the functionality in action.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>World Clock</title>
    <style>
        body {
            display: flex;
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            margin: 0;
            height: 100vh;
            background-color: #f0f0f0;
        }
        .clock {
            flex: 1;
            display: flex;
            justify-content: center;
            align-items: center;
            font-size: 5rem;
            background-color: white;
            border-right: 2px solid #ccc;
        }
        .sidebar {
            width: 300px;
            padding: 20px;
            background-color: #e0e0e0;
        }
        .sidebar h2 {
            margin-top: 0;
        }
        .city-clock {
            margin: 10px 0;
            font-size: 2rem;
        }
        input[type="text"] {
            width: calc(100% - 22px);
            padding: 10px;
            margin: 10px 0;
        }
        button {
            padding: 10px;
            width: 100%;
            background-color: #28a745;
            color: white;
            border: none;
            cursor: pointer;
        }
        button:hover {
            background-color: #218838;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

<div class="clock" id="local-time"></div>
<div class="sidebar">
    <h2>World Clocks</h2>
    <div id="city-clocks"></div>
    <input type="text" id="city-input" placeholder="Add new city">
    <button id="add-city">Add City</button>
</div>

<script>
    const localTimeDisplay = document.getElementById('local-time');
    const cityClocksDisplay = document.getElementById('city-clocks');
    const cityInput = document.getElementById('city-input');
    const addCityButton = document.getElementById('add-city');

    const timezones = [
        { city: 'London', timezone: 'Europe/London' },
        { city: 'New York', timezone: 'America/New_York' },
        { city: 'Tokyo', timezone: 'Asia/Tokyo' },
        { city: 'Sydney', timezone: 'Australia/Sydney' },
    ];

    const loadCityClocks = () => {
        cityClocksDisplay.innerHTML = '';
        const storedCities = JSON.parse(localStorage.getItem('cities')) || [];
        const allCities = [...timezones, ...storedCities];

        allCities.forEach(({ city, timezone }) => {
            const clockDiv = document.createElement('div');
            clockDiv.classList.add('city-clock');
            clockDiv.textContent = `${city}: ${getTime(timezone)}`;
            cityClocksDisplay.appendChild(clockDiv);
        });
    };

    const getTime = (timezone) => {
        return new Date().toLocaleString('en-US', { timeZone: timezone, hour: '2-digit', minute: '2-digit', second: '2-digit' });
    };

    const updateLocalTime = () => {
        const localDateTime = new Date().toLocaleString();
        localTimeDisplay.textContent = localDateTime;
    };

    const addCity = () => {
        const newCityName = cityInput.value.trim();
        if (newCityName) {
            const newCityData = { city: newCityName, timezone: `Etc/GMT` }; // Placeholder timezone
            const storedCities = JSON.parse(localStorage.getItem('cities')) || [];
            storedCities.push(newCityData);
            localStorage.setItem('cities', JSON.stringify(storedCities));
            cityInput.value = '';
            loadCityClocks();
        }
    };

    addCityButton.addEventListener('click', addCity);
    setInterval(updateLocalTime, 1000);
    setInterval(loadCityClocks, 1000);

    // Initialize clocks
    loadCityClocks();
    updateLocalTime();
</script>

</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation:
1. **HTML Structure**: The document contains a large display for local time and a sidebar for world clocks.
2. **CSS Styles**: Styles are embedded directly in the `<style>` tag to define the layout and appearance of the clocks and input fields.
3. **JavaScript Functionality**:
   - The code retrieves stored cities from `localStorage` to display them.
   - It uses the JavaScript `setInterval` method to keep the local time and world clocks updated every second.
   - When you input a city name and click the "Add City" button, it stores the city name in `localStorage`, and the display gets updated.

### Note:
- For simplicity, newly added cities currently default to a timezone of `Etc/GMT`; you may modify this to allow users to specify their timezones.

